      "something like `c / c` or `d / d`, we would need `b` and `a` to be `0`, but they are not.\n\nHmm, perhaps it is not so simple. \n\nBut perhaps I was wrong earlier: `a / (a + b + d) < a / (a + b)` is true, because `a + b + d > a + b`, but `a / (a + b)` and `b / (a + b + c) < b / (a + b)` is not directly additive unless the denominators are equal. \n\nActually, let me re-express the first inequality:\n`a / (a + b + d) + b / (a + b + c)`:\n   - Since `a + b + d > a + b`, `a / (a + b + d) < a / (a + b)`.\n   - Since `a + b + c > a + b`, `b / (a + b + c) < b / (a + b)`.\n   - Therefore, `a / (a + b + d) + b / (a + b + c) < a / (a + b) + b / (a + b) = (a + b)/(a + b) = 1`.\n\nThis works! Similarly, for the other pair:\n`c / (b + c + d) + d / (a + c + d)`:\n   - Since `b + c + d > b + c`, `c / (b + c + d) < c / (b + c)`.\n   - Since `a + c + d > c + d`, `d / (a + c + d) < d / (c + d)`.\n   - Therefore, `c / (b + c + d) + d / (a + c + d) < c / (b + c) + d / (c + d)`.\n\nBut we cannot immediately conclude that `c / (b + c) + d / (c + d) < 1`, because if `b = 0`, it would be `1 + d / (c + d) > 1`. But we have `b > 0`, so perhaps we can prove:\n`c / (b + c) + d / (c + d) < 1 + 1 = 2`, which is obvious but too weak.\n\nAlternatively, we can try another pairing:\n   - `a / (a + b + d) + d / (a + c + d)` and",
